====================================================================
DOCKER VOLUMES 
====================================================================

--------------------------------------------------
WHAT IS A DOCKER VOLUME?
--------------------------------------------------

    Docker Volume is a storage mechanism
    used to persist container data.

    By default:

        Container data is temporary.

    If container is deleted:

        Data is also deleted ❌

    Volumes solve this problem ✅


--------------------------------------------------
WHY DO WE NEED VOLUMES?
--------------------------------------------------

    Containers are ephemeral (temporary).

    Without volume:

        Container deleted → Data lost

    With volume:

        Data survives even if container is removed


--------------------------------------------------
SIMPLE USE CASE
--------------------------------------------------

    Scenario:

        MySQL container stores database data.

    Without volume:

        Container removed → Database lost ❌

    With volume:

        Data stored outside container ✅


--------------------------------------------------
HOW VOLUMES WORK
--------------------------------------------------

    Container
        ↓
    Mounted volume
        ↓
    Data stored on host machine


--------------------------------------------------
TYPES OF DOCKER STORAGE
--------------------------------------------------

    1) Volumes
    2) Bind Mounts
	3) 


--------------------------------------------------
1) DOCKER VOLUMES (RECOMMENDED)
--------------------------------------------------

    Managed by Docker.

    Stored in:

        /var/lib/docker/volumes/

Example:

    docker volume create myvolume

Run container:

    docker run -d  -v myvolume:/app/data  nginx


--------------------------------------------------
2) BIND MOUNTS
--------------------------------------------------

    Maps host directory directly  into container.

Example:

    docker run -d -v /opt/logs:/opt/los amazonlinux

    Left side:
        Host path

    Right side:
        Container path


--------------------------------------------------
3) TMPFS MOUNTS
--------------------------------------------------

    Temporary in-memory storage.

    Data lost after container stops.


--------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT DOCKER VOLUME COMMANDS
--------------------------------------------------

Create volume:

    docker volume create myvolume

List volumes:

    docker volume ls

Inspect volume:

    docker volume inspect myvolume

Remove volume:

    docker volume rm myvolume


--------------------------------------------------
REAL DEVOPS USE CASES
--------------------------------------------------

    • Database persistence
    • Jenkins home directory
    • Shared logs
    • Application uploads
    • Persistent configs


--------------------------------------------------
JENKINS EXAMPLE
--------------------------------------------------

    docker run -d -p 8080:8080 -v jenkisdata:/var/jenkins_home  jenkins/jenkins:lts

    Jenkins data remains safe even
    if container restarts.


--------------------------------------------------
VOLUME VS BIND MOUNT
--------------------------------------------------

    Volume:

        • Managed by Docker
        • More portable
        • Recommended

    Bind Mount:

        • Direct host path
        • More control
        • Host dependent


--------------------------------------------------
ADVANTAGES OF VOLUMES
--------------------------------------------------

    • Persistent storage
    • Data survives container deletion
    • Easy backup
    • Share data between containers


--------------------------------------------------
SIMPLE SUMMARY
--------------------------------------------------

    Docker Volume = Persistent container storage

    Purpose:
        Keep data safe outside container

